    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_196342376" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/196342376" />
    <a title="Megha" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1727205-megha"><img alt="Megha" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1361664925p2/1727205.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/196342376?book_show_action=true">Aug 08, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Megha" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Megha" href="/user/show/1727205-megha">Megha</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook " href="/book/show/8519525-a-visit-from-the-goon-squad">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1727205-megha?shelf=its-not-you-its-me">its-not-you-its-me</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1727205-megha?shelf=reviews">reviews</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer196342376" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12250053821227748919">Time is a goon? Not necessarily, I think.<br/><br/>( First of all, I think I may be too un-American to really get this book. The dreams, hopes, expectations, definition of a happy and content life for most Indians are entirely different from all of Egan&apos;s characters. These stories won&apos;t fit in an Indian context. This may be a reason why this book didn&apos;t speak to me the same way as it did to many other readers. )<br/><br/>I can&apos;t help feeling that at least some of Egan&apos;s characters were responsible for wrecking thei</span>
  <span id="freeText12250053821227748919" style="display:none">Time is a goon? Not necessarily, I think.<br /><br />( First of all, I think I may be too un-American to really get this book. The dreams, hopes, expectations, definition of a happy and content life for most Indians are entirely different from all of Egan's characters. These stories won't fit in an Indian context. This may be a reason why this book didn't speak to me the same way as it did to many other readers. )<br /><br />I can't help feeling that at least some of Egan's characters were responsible for wrecking their own lives. They just didn't make an honest attempt to build livable lives for themselves. Yeah sure, circumstances don't always work in one's favor. But how our lives shape up also depends on the numerous big and small choices we make for ourselves. It also depends on people around us because our lives are cross-wired with many others. It is not right to blame time and luck for everything that goes wrong. True, unfortunate circumstances can at times push one in a dark corner, for none of their own fault. Some people do have worse luck than most others. But one cannot keep using that as an excuse for every wrong step they take. At some point they have to stop grieving, pull their lives together and do the best they can with whatever cards they have been dealt. Whatever happened to <i>time is the best healer</i>?<br />Times do change. But the change is not necessarily bad. Not for everyone, at least. Some people get rude shocks, some others hit upon unexpectedly good fortune. It works both ways. We gain something new, we leave something behind. We learn to live with the flow of the time. It is one thing to have hopes and ambitions, and plan things out for future. But it is too much to expect for time to follow our rhythms and pauses and ensure that our plans are executed perfectly. No matter what <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/865.The_Alchemist" rel="nofollow noopener">Paulo Coelho</a> says, the universe may not actually be conspiring to make every single person's wishes come true.<br /><br />Another of Egan's concerns is regarding rapidly changing lifestyle, ways of communication and our dependence on technology. Yes, that is happening alright. Don't we all know it! And we also know that similar things have been happening for generations. My parents grew up without TV or (any kind of) phone. Surely they didn't expect to see a day when smart-phones and laptops will begin to be just as essential possessions as a toothbrush. Likewise, we can't know what exactly the world around us will be like when we are a generation older. Some changes will make things easier, others will give rise to anxieties. And again, we will learn to live with the times. People always have.<br /><br />One more reason why Egan's thoughts didn't come across very well is that her theme had to constantly vie for attention with her stylized structure. I did really like her use of non-linear time-line and kaleidoscopic manner of presenting certain pieces of the character's lives. But the novel's form also felt like she had just come out of week-long writing workshop and was eager to show off every single style she had learnt. <br /><br />However, I must say, this book is not merely popular, it also has a literary gene in it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12250053821227748919" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


